  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q099",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "disk-storage",
    "stem": "Before a disk drive can access any sector record, a computer program has to provide the record’s disk address. What information does this address specify?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Track number",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Sector number",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Surface number",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "All of above",
        "isCorrect": true
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "D"
    ],
    "explanation": "This is classic CHS addressing: a sector is uniquely located only by naming the surface (which platter side, i.e. which head), the track (cylinder) on that surface, and the sector within that track. Any single one of the three is insufficient, so \"all of above\" is correct.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 9
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "7debe9f2565b5f73513a0a1a5d9e9602b93719aa"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-b-q100",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "disk-storage",
    "stem": "As compared to diskettes, the hard disks are",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "More expensive",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "More portable",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Less rigid",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Slowly accessed",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "Compared with diskettes, hard disks are fixed and rigid (not portable, not less rigid) and have far faster access, so the only remaining true statement is that they cost more. Legacy item, decided by elimination.",
    "source": {
      "file": "Computer Engineering K-Companies Exam - Questions.pdf",
